column1: #Text=So , how 's the movement in the right arm today ?
#Text=I still do n't have full movement in it .
#Text=And I 've had nine surgeries on it to date .
#Text=You still ca n't fully flex the right hand .

#Text=I also in 2006 was readmitted back to hospital with another episode of transverse myelitis , which is my original disability , which then left me a C5 incomplete quad , so it then affected my right arm , in addition to the elbow injury .
#Text=So , I 've now got weakness in my triceps , biceps , and weakness in my hand on my right side .
#Text=And that was following the birth of my son .
#Text=I had him in July 2005 , and then was readmitted to hospital in early 2006 with another episode of transverse myelitis .
#Text=And it has a higher incidence of recurring post pregnancy .
#Text=And I was both , at the same time .
#Text=So you gave up wheelchair basketball after the 2000 games ?
#Text=I had the first surgery so I literally arrived back in Melbourne and on to an operating table for the ruptured tendons .

#Text=Spent the next nine months in hospital from that surgery . So I had the surgery and then went to rehab for nine months , inpatient , so it was a big admission , because I also had a complication where I grew heterotopic bone into the elbow , so that was also causing some of the sticking and things .
#Text=And then went back to a camp probably around 2002 , and was selected to go overseas .

#Text=And at that point got a pressure sore , and decided not to travel , because I thought the risk of travelling with the pressure sore was an additional complication , and at that point APC were also saying that if I was to go overseas , because I had a " pre existing " elbow injury , that they would n't cover me insurance-wise .
#Text=So I though : " hmmm Do I go overseas ?
